00:37:08.038 --> 00:37:09.967
and the European Research Council,

00:37:09.967 --> 00:37:11.719
and with that, I thank
you for your attention,

00:37:11.719 --> 00:37:13.840
and I am curious which
questions you will write down.

00:37:13.840 --> 00:37:16.567
(applause)

00:37:16.567 --> 00:37:19.846
My job at the beginning at
least is a little simplified

00:37:19.846 --> 00:37:22.919
because of the talks
you've heard from already,

00:37:22.919 --> 00:37:26.086
especially from Rick and from Wieland.

00:37:26.983 --> 00:37:29.629
As you all are well aware,
the human brain is the largest

00:37:29.629 --> 00:37:32.671
among primates, living primates.

00:37:32.671 --> 00:37:33.975
I just wanted to emphasize it's not

00:37:33.975 --> 00:37:36.315
the largest mammal brain.

00:37:36.315 --> 00:37:38.964
Elephants and whales and
cetaceans have larger,

00:37:38.964 --> 00:37:41.981
and also more highly
folded cerebral cortices,

00:37:41.981 --> 00:37:45.071
but in terms of brain number
in the cerebral cortex,

00:37:45.071 --> 00:37:48.198
neuron number, humans have
the largest total number.

00:37:48.198 --> 00:37:51.429
So my area of interest,
similar to Wieland's is,

00:37:51.429 --> 00:37:54.935
one of the more obvious
features of the human brain

00:37:54.935 --> 00:37:57.055
is its size and the number of cells,

00:37:57.055 --> 00:37:59.031
and that brings us right to the issue of

00:37:59.031 --> 00:38:01.382
where they all come from, which has been,

00:38:01.382 --> 00:38:02.865
as you hear, a sort of interesting problem

00:38:02.865 --> 00:38:05.487
or central problem for many of us.

00:38:05.487 --> 00:38:08.401
The developmental stages
are clearly where we'll

00:38:08.401 --> 00:38:10.364
find the answer to how that happens,

00:38:10.364 --> 00:38:13.013
and in my lab, we've been
looking at human brain

00:38:13.013 --> 00:38:15.551
development through the second trimester,

00:38:15.551 --> 00:38:18.498
which is when most cortical
neurons are developed.

00:38:18.498 --> 00:38:21.487
Cross section through the
developing cortex looks

00:38:21.487 --> 00:38:22.919
very different in humans than it does,

00:38:22.919 --> 00:38:25.678
for example in a mouse,
which is the animal system

00:38:25.678 --> 00:38:28.165
that most neuroscientists
have used to study

00:38:28.165 --> 00:38:30.631
early stages of brain development.

00:38:30.631 --> 00:38:32.382
So this is the cross section of the mouse,

00:38:32.382 --> 00:38:33.702
and you heard from
Wieland very beautifully

00:38:33.702 --> 00:38:36.615
how there are apical progenitors
which we call radial glia,

00:38:36.615 --> 00:38:39.165
shown here in red, marked by Sox2,

00:38:39.165 --> 00:38:41.665
one of the transcription
factors that they express,

00:38:41.665 --> 00:38:43.328
and their daughter cells are these

00:38:43.328 --> 00:38:45.855
intermediate progenitors
that line up right above them

00:38:45.855 --> 00:38:47.687
in this subventricular zone.

00:38:47.687 --> 00:38:49.606
The beginning, the middle,
and the end of neurogenesis

00:38:49.606 --> 00:38:51.783
in the mouse looks just like that.

00:38:51.783 --> 00:38:54.223
In the human, it starts
out very similarly.

00:38:54.223 --> 00:38:56.365
There are radial glial cells
and intermediate progenitors

00:38:56.365 --> 00:38:58.582
forming these two layers,

00:38:58.582 --> 00:39:01.151
but then very rapidly,
the subventricular zone

00:39:01.151 --> 00:39:04.111
undergoes this enormous
expansion that you've heard about

00:39:04.111 --> 00:39:07.246
and becomes an outer
subventricular zone shown here,

00:39:07.246 --> 00:39:09.615
and all these colors represent
cells that are cycling.

00:39:09.615 --> 00:39:11.615
They're producing daughter cells.

00:39:11.615 --> 00:39:13.455
You may notice the
ventricular zone at this stage

00:39:13.455 --> 00:39:15.748
becomes very small, and so the majority

00:39:15.748 --> 00:39:18.593
of cortical neurons at these
stages almost certainly

00:39:18.593 --> 00:39:22.077
are coming from this zone,
not from the ventricular zone.

00:39:22.077 --> 00:39:23.997
And moreover, this isn't
the end of neurogenesis.

00:39:23.997 --> 00:39:26.735
This is half-way through gestation week 17

00:39:26.735 --> 00:39:28.687
when the middle layers are being formed.

00:39:28.687 --> 00:39:30.825
So the middle and upper
cortical layers are

00:39:30.825 --> 00:39:33.068
presumably being generated by the cells in

00:39:33.068 --> 00:39:35.259
this outer subventricular zone.

00:39:35.259 --> 00:39:36.979
But the actual nature of those progenitors

00:39:36.979 --> 00:39:39.838
really haven't been studied,
and so we looked at it

00:39:39.838 --> 00:39:41.501
in a variety of ways.

00:39:41.501 --> 00:39:44.242
First I want to show you
how dynamic this area is.

00:39:44.242 --> 00:39:46.577
In this case, we're looking at
the outer subventricular zone

00:39:46.577 --> 00:39:48.611
in a slice culture where we've labeled

00:39:48.611 --> 00:39:51.320
just the progenitor cells in green,

00:39:51.320 --> 00:39:52.621
so there are neurons we don't see.

00:39:52.621 --> 00:39:55.274
But the progenitors are highly dynamic.

00:39:55.274 --> 00:39:56.827
When we look at them more carefully,

00:39:56.827 --> 00:39:58.857
we find two classes, and
one that I really want

00:39:58.857 --> 00:40:00.347
to emphasize is this one.

00:40:00.347 --> 00:40:03.055
It's a radial glia-like cell.

00:40:03.055 --> 00:40:05.259
It has a process that goes
up to the pia surface,

00:40:05.259 --> 00:40:06.707
which is the basal fiber,

00:40:06.707 --> 00:40:08.266
but it doesn't have an apical contact

00:40:08.266 --> 00:40:10.765
with the ventricle the
way the epithelial cells

00:40:10.765 --> 00:40:13.865
or the ventricular or
apical radial glia do.

00:40:13.865 --> 00:40:16.006
Otherwise it looks just
like a radial glial cell.

00:40:16.006 --> 00:40:18.344
It stains with all the markers
that you normally would see

00:40:18.344 --> 00:40:20.771
in radial glial cells,
and if you back-fill

00:40:20.771 --> 00:40:24.232
the surface of the cortex
with a label like this,

00:40:24.232 --> 00:40:27.424
the DiI crystal, it fills
the fibers of these cells

00:40:27.424 --> 00:40:31.265
that end in cell bodies in
the outer subventricular zone.

00:40:31.265 --> 00:40:33.358
These cells hadn't been
described at the time,

00:40:33.358 --> 00:40:37.123
so we call them outer subventricular
radial glia-like cells

00:40:37.123 --> 00:40:39.089
or ORG cells, and as you heard,

00:40:39.089 --> 00:40:41.224
Wieland calls them basal radial glia.

00:40:41.224 --> 00:40:43.488
They're the same cell
type, and they're enriched,

00:40:43.488 --> 00:40:47.856
it turns out, in the
human developing brain.

00:40:47.856 --> 00:40:49.544
Now we've looked at them dynamically,

00:40:49.544 --> 00:40:52.905
and were struck by a behavior
that hadn't been seen before.

00:40:52.905 --> 00:40:55.712
These are four of the
cells that are labeled

00:40:55.712 --> 00:40:59.295
in one slice of cortex,
and as they divide,

00:41:00.738 --> 00:41:03.037
you may notice how they
sort of jump and divide,

00:41:03.037 --> 00:41:04.911
and if you didn't notice
it in those images,

00:41:04.911 --> 00:41:07.792
I hope you'll be able to
see it in this single cell.

00:41:07.792 --> 00:41:09.728
Because as they go through M phase,

00:41:09.728 --> 00:41:12.247
the actual cytokinesis
stage when they divide,

00:41:12.247 --> 00:41:14.473
they jump first and then undergo this

00:41:14.473 --> 00:41:16.806
cell division or cytokinesis.

00:41:16.806 --> 00:41:18.896
Very distinctive behavior
that hadn't been described

00:41:18.896 --> 00:41:22.760
before, and so we called it
mitotic somal translocation, MST

00:41:22.760 --> 00:41:26.338
and it was one of the defining
features of these cells

00:41:26.338 --> 00:41:28.722
because there were no specific
markers that we could use

00:41:28.722 --> 00:41:30.739
to distinguish them from the traditional

00:41:30.739 --> 00:41:33.206
ventricular radial glia.

00:41:33.206 --> 00:41:34.607
But when we looked for
them in other species,

00:41:34.607 --> 00:41:37.607
and this is in the mouse,
we found them there as well,

00:41:37.607 --> 00:41:40.848
and if you watch the cell,
it's what we call now

00:41:40.848 --> 00:41:43.494
a mouse outer radial glial cell,

00:41:43.494 --> 00:41:45.952
and you see it goes through a little jump,

00:41:45.952 --> 00:41:48.217
much more modest than the human cells.

00:41:48.217 --> 00:41:50.089
It has this basal fiber, and it's located

00:41:50.089 --> 00:41:52.606
in the subventricular
zone if the mouse had

00:41:52.606 --> 00:41:54.631
a subventricular zone.

00:41:54.631 --> 00:41:57.079
So these cells are present in
small numbers in the mouse,

00:41:57.079 --> 00:42:00.176
and are usually expanded in primates,

00:42:00.176 --> 00:42:02.592
and especially in humans.

00:42:02.592 --> 00:42:03.703
Are they neurogenic?

00:42:03.703 --> 00:42:05.204
Do they actually make neurons?

00:42:05.204 --> 00:42:07.752
And to test that, we
actually dissociated cells

00:42:07.752 --> 00:42:10.388
from the progenitor
zones, labeled them with

00:42:10.388 --> 00:42:14.351
a virus marker that actually
just infected progenitors,

00:42:14.351 --> 00:42:17.508
and then put a single progenitor
in each multi-well place,

00:42:17.508 --> 00:42:19.740
and here's an example of a
single one of the progenitors

00:42:19.740 --> 00:42:23.172
in this well, and a higher
magnification view is there.

00:42:23.172 --> 00:42:25.523
Then we time-lapse imaged the behavior,

00:42:25.523 --> 00:42:27.418
and you could identify
the outer radial glia

00:42:27.418 --> 00:42:28.867
by their first division.

00:42:28.867 --> 00:42:30.724
They put out a primary
process just like they would

00:42:30.724 --> 00:42:33.508
in in situ, and then
they jumped and divided,

00:42:33.508 --> 00:42:38.302
and that made that cell classified
as an outer radial glia.

00:42:38.302 --> 00:42:40.092
We had other cells that
rounded up and divided.

00:42:40.092 --> 00:42:41.485
Those were the intermediate progenitors,

00:42:41.485 --> 00:42:43.899
and we looked seven weeks later in culture

00:42:43.899 --> 00:42:45.276
at what the clones were like.

00:42:45.276 --> 00:42:48.172
What does a single outer radial glia cell

00:42:48.172 --> 00:42:50.668
actually produce, at least in vitro?

00:42:50.668 --> 00:42:52.476
And the answer was really surprising.

00:42:52.476 --> 00:42:54.556
The cells I showed you, after seven weeks,

00:42:54.556 --> 00:42:56.988
have produced a clone
of at least 700 cells,

00:42:56.988 --> 00:42:58.643
which included neurons of both

00:42:58.643 --> 00:43:01.035
deeper and upper cortical layers.

00:43:01.035 --> 00:43:02.699
And in this clone, there
were no astrocytes,

00:43:02.699 --> 00:43:05.136
and some of the clones that
were additionally astrocytes

00:43:05.136 --> 00:43:09.540
plus neurons, and this is
an enormous output of cells.

00:43:09.540 --> 00:43:11.788
If we do the same experiment
with a radial glial cell

00:43:11.788 --> 00:43:16.108
in a mouse, we get 20 to 40
cells after a month or so.

00:43:16.108 --> 00:43:20.334
So 700 to 1000 cells from a
single outer radial glial cell,

00:43:20.334 --> 00:43:24.045
I think underscores how
enormously proliferative

00:43:24.045 --> 00:43:25.485
these cells are.

00:43:25.485 --> 00:43:28.140
And so it helps support this model

00:43:28.140 --> 00:43:29.859
which is still a work in progress

00:43:29.859 --> 00:43:31.636
of what we think makes
human cortical development

00:43:31.636 --> 00:43:33.701
distinct from say the mouse.

00:43:33.701 --> 00:43:36.872
And in the ventricular and
subventricular zones shown here,

00:43:36.872 --> 00:43:40.052
we think cells in human behave
very much like the mouse,

00:43:40.052 --> 00:43:42.660
but what makes the human so distinct

00:43:42.660 --> 00:43:44.419
is the outer subventricular zone,

00:43:44.419 --> 00:43:46.306
which is filled with
these outer radial glia

00:43:46.306 --> 00:43:48.217
which are born initially
from the ventricular zone

00:43:48.217 --> 00:43:51.619
and move away, and they
go through these multiple

00:43:51.619 --> 00:43:53.740
self-renewing asymmetrical divisions,

00:43:53.740 --> 00:43:56.786
producing these daughters,
shown here in green,

00:43:56.786 --> 00:43:59.556
which are transit
amplifying progenitor cells,

00:43:59.556 --> 00:44:02.508
and they actually divide
symmetrically at least twice.

00:44:02.508 --> 00:44:04.292
We know they do that more than once,

00:44:04.292 --> 00:44:06.519
producing clones of cells which then have

00:44:06.519 --> 00:44:08.369
the same birthdate and migrate, therefore,

00:44:08.369 --> 00:44:10.075
to the same cortical layer.

00:44:10.075 --> 00:44:12.619
And over time, one of these
ORG cells will produce

00:44:12.619 --> 00:44:16.571
multiple clones of cells in
multiple different layers.

00:44:16.571 --> 00:44:19.508
And the radial fibers
support neuronal migration.

00:44:19.508 --> 00:44:22.234
So that allows an increase
in the cortical size

00:44:22.234 --> 00:44:24.269
tangentially as well as radially.

00:44:24.269 --> 00:44:25.523
So we think this cell is very important

00:44:25.523 --> 00:44:27.802
for cortical expansion
both developmentally,

00:44:27.802 --> 00:44:31.635
as shown here, and also
in evolutionary terms.

00:44:32.770 --> 00:44:34.922
But as I said, we had no
markers for these cells.

00:44:34.922 --> 00:44:37.187
We had no real idea of
what made them distinct

00:44:37.187 --> 00:44:39.692
molecularly from the
ventricular radial glia

00:44:39.692 --> 00:44:41.719
for example in the mouse.

00:44:41.719 --> 00:44:43.586
So we took as an approach for this

00:44:43.586 --> 00:44:45.387
is single cell RNA sequencing.

00:44:45.387 --> 00:44:48.634
So we dissociated early cells, shown here,

00:44:48.634 --> 00:44:50.947
took those individual
cells and collected them

00:44:50.947 --> 00:44:55.114
in microliter tiny little
nano-sized capture sites

00:44:59.385 --> 00:45:01.036
in a chip, a microfluidic chip

00:45:01.036 --> 00:45:03.875
which is made by Fluidyne Corporation,

00:45:03.875 --> 00:45:06.002
and when they're captured
in these little sites,

00:45:06.002 --> 00:45:09.187
you can then do lysis
and reverse transcription

00:45:09.187 --> 00:45:11.659
and amplify them and
then sequence the genes

00:45:11.659 --> 00:45:13.915
for each individual cell.

00:45:13.915 --> 00:45:15.702
And that's an unbiased way,
that is we take all comers

00:45:15.702 --> 00:45:19.153
and see what those gene
differences look like.

00:45:19.153 --> 00:45:21.187
Here is an example of a heed map

00:45:21.187 --> 00:45:23.387
where we have the cells in all these rows

00:45:23.387 --> 00:45:26.352
and genes in columns, and
you can see how they cluster

00:45:26.352 --> 00:45:28.421
according to the genes that they express,

00:45:28.421 --> 00:45:31.903
and that allows us to identify
molecular characteristics

00:45:31.903 --> 00:45:34.569
of specific cell types.

00:45:34.569 --> 00:45:36.236
And just to look at
some of the progenitors,

00:45:36.236 --> 00:45:38.109
and this is when we first
did our initial study

00:45:38.109 --> 00:45:41.421
of about 300 cells that
were captured this way,

00:45:41.421 --> 00:45:43.830
we can see three different cell states.

00:45:43.830 --> 00:45:46.173
Here in the lower left are
the radial glial genes,

00:45:46.173 --> 00:45:49.341
the ones that are the most
enriched in radial glial cells.

00:45:49.341 --> 00:45:51.373
In the brackets are the
intermediate progenitors,

00:45:51.373 --> 00:45:53.173
which are the daughters
of the radial glia,

00:45:53.173 --> 00:45:55.084
and then here on the
right on the upper side

00:45:55.084 --> 00:45:58.708
are the enriched genes mostly
in young immature neurons.

00:45:58.708 --> 00:46:00.484
What this shows us is that some genes

00:46:00.484 --> 00:46:03.168
that are initially
expressed in the radial glia

00:46:03.168 --> 00:46:05.005
persist in their daughter cells,

00:46:05.005 --> 00:46:07.196
the intermediate progenitors,
and genes that are expressed

00:46:07.196 --> 00:46:10.701
in those progenitors persist
as neurons are produced.

00:46:10.701 --> 00:46:12.907
This is very useful in a
way because it helps us

00:46:12.907 --> 00:46:15.122
watch the lineage of each of these cells.

00:46:15.122 --> 00:46:17.860
So an example shown here actually confirms

00:46:17.860 --> 00:46:19.970
what we saw from the time-lapse imaging.

00:46:19.970 --> 00:46:21.508
Radial glial cells shown here on the left

00:46:21.508 --> 00:46:23.740
producing intermediate progenitors

00:46:23.740 --> 00:46:25.690
which then generate neurons,
and these are some of the genes

00:46:25.690 --> 00:46:28.106
both known and new genes expressed

00:46:28.106 --> 00:46:30.299
at each of these different stages.

00:46:30.299 --> 00:46:32.331
We confirm the expression of the new genes

00:46:32.331 --> 00:46:35.202
by in situ hybridization
shown here in slices.

00:46:35.202 --> 00:46:37.511
Genes that we predict would
be expressed in radial glia

00:46:37.511 --> 00:46:39.362
are located here at the ventricle.

00:46:39.362 --> 00:46:41.267
Genes expressed in
intermediate progenitors

00:46:41.267 --> 00:46:44.187
or radial glia are expressed here,

00:46:44.187 --> 00:46:46.563
and then the neural genes are expressed

00:46:46.563 --> 00:46:48.394
in the cortical plate.

00:46:48.394 --> 00:46:52.356
Now not only did this give
us an idea of the transition

00:46:52.356 --> 00:46:55.482
or lineage of cell types,
but it gave us insight into

00:46:55.482 --> 00:46:58.365
activated gene networks that
might actually be signaling

00:46:58.365 --> 00:47:00.095
individual cell types, and to focus on the

00:47:00.095 --> 00:47:02.922
outer radial glia for this talk.

00:47:02.922 --> 00:47:05.997
These are all schematically shown genes

00:47:05.997 --> 00:47:08.770
that are coherent in networks
expressed exclusively

00:47:08.770 --> 00:47:12.600
by outer radial glia at
these developmental stages,

00:47:12.600 --> 00:47:15.381
and one of those gene
networks and pathways

00:47:15.381 --> 00:47:17.797
is the LIFR STAT3 signaling pathway

00:47:17.797 --> 00:47:19.996
known to most stem cell biologists

00:47:19.996 --> 00:47:22.649
as an important self-renewal pathway.

00:47:22.649 --> 00:47:24.419
So we find that these
outer radial glia cells

00:47:24.419 --> 00:47:26.565
are actually able to self-renew themselves

00:47:26.565 --> 00:47:28.201
and create their own niche.

00:47:28.201 --> 00:47:31.332
If we inhibit this pathway,
as shown here on these graphs

00:47:31.332 --> 00:47:33.532
on the lower right, we
significantly inhibit

00:47:33.532 --> 00:47:36.427
the generation of the radial glial cells,

00:47:36.427 --> 00:47:38.196
but not the intermediate progenitors,

00:47:38.196 --> 00:47:40.186
or for that matter, the
ventricular radial glia.

00:47:40.186 --> 00:47:42.491
So it's selective to this one cell type.

00:47:42.491 --> 00:47:44.905
And it helps support an idea shown here

00:47:44.905 --> 00:47:48.080
that distinguishes the
human from the mouse.

00:47:48.080 --> 00:47:50.666
In the mouse, as you
know, as we just heard,

00:47:50.666 --> 00:47:53.138
they have radial glial cells
and intermediate progenitors

00:47:53.138 --> 00:47:54.954
and the radial glial
cells line the ventricle

00:47:54.954 --> 00:47:56.932
where they can receive
trophic factor signaling

00:47:56.932 --> 00:47:59.557
from the CSF, cerebrospinal fluid.

00:47:59.557 --> 00:48:02.178
In the outer subventricular
zone, the cells

00:48:02.178 --> 00:48:04.357
have actually moved
away from the ventricle,

00:48:04.357 --> 00:48:07.036
and they're not able to
access the growth factors

00:48:07.036 --> 00:48:09.994
in the CSF, but instead,
they develop their own

00:48:09.994 --> 00:48:11.358
signaling pathways.

00:48:11.358 --> 00:48:12.962
They can produce their own growth factors,

00:48:12.962 --> 00:48:14.375
and they create their own niche

00:48:14.375 --> 00:48:16.875
for self-renewal and expansion.

00:48:16.875 --> 00:48:18.776
We think that that is one
of the reasons, of course,

00:48:18.776 --> 00:48:20.674
that these cells were able to undergo

00:48:20.674 --> 00:48:23.761
the kind of prolonged
and massive proliferation

00:48:23.761 --> 00:48:27.778
that I've shown you and that
Wieland mentioned earlier.

00:48:27.778 --> 00:48:30.192
We've also gotten some
insights into diseases,

00:48:30.192 --> 00:48:32.298
and I just want to mention
two of them very quickly.

00:48:32.298 --> 00:48:33.907
One of them is this.

00:48:33.907 --> 00:48:36.391
And as I've just mentioned,
these outer radial glial cells

00:48:36.391 --> 00:48:38.562
make their own niche, and
they have factors that

00:48:38.562 --> 00:48:42.196
promote self-renewal, and when
we looked at all these genes

00:48:42.196 --> 00:48:43.711
in the literature, we
found that they'd all been

00:48:43.711 --> 00:48:46.282
reported earlier or already discovered

00:48:46.282 --> 00:48:48.541
in this particular kind of tumor,

00:48:48.541 --> 00:48:50.938
the glioblastoma multiforme,
which is a terrible

00:48:50.938 --> 00:48:54.457
and inoperable brain
tumor found in adults,

00:48:54.457 --> 00:48:56.503
not in children.

00:48:56.503 --> 00:48:57.957
But when we look
carefully at the published

00:48:57.957 --> 00:49:00.250
single cell heed maps, like this one,

00:49:00.250 --> 00:49:04.141
for radial glial genes,
rather for genes that are

00:49:04.141 --> 00:49:06.774
expressed in tumors as
well as radial glia,

00:49:06.774 --> 00:49:09.194
we cross those reference points,

00:49:09.194 --> 00:49:13.194
we found that in fact, the
most aggressive glioblastomas

00:49:13.194 --> 00:49:15.194
were enriched in the
same genes that we found

00:49:15.194 --> 00:49:17.824
in the outer radial glial cells.

00:49:17.824 --> 00:49:20.941
They had apparently an
outer radial glial signature

00:49:20.941 --> 00:49:24.497
in the most aggressive
grade of glioblastoma.

00:49:24.497 --> 00:49:27.058
So then we looked in surgical specimens

00:49:27.058 --> 00:49:29.239
that we got from our colleagues at UCSF,

00:49:29.239 --> 00:49:31.613
sectioned and stained, and cultured them

00:49:31.613 --> 00:49:33.836
just like we had primary tissue,

00:49:33.836 --> 00:49:35.978
and shown here are glioblastoma cells

00:49:35.978 --> 00:49:37.605
from one of the patients.

00:49:37.605 --> 00:49:39.948
And focus your attention on this cell

00:49:39.948 --> 00:49:42.031
as it undergoes division.

00:49:44.316 --> 00:49:45.164
I hope you can see it.

00:49:45.164 --> 00:49:45.997
Yeah, there it is.

00:49:45.997 --> 00:49:47.173
Watch that one.

00:49:47.173 --> 00:49:48.378
Here we go.

00:49:48.378 --> 00:49:50.331
Right, so you may have
noticed how it jumped

00:49:50.331 --> 00:49:53.748
and divided exactly like
the fetal cells do in situ.

00:49:53.748 --> 00:49:56.220
So it looks as if we have
outer radial glial cells

00:49:56.220 --> 00:49:58.819
in these glioblastomas
and in fact, that work has

00:49:58.819 --> 00:50:01.564
progressed to the point where
we now have good evidence

00:50:01.564 --> 00:50:04.626
that these may be the cells of origin for

00:50:04.626 --> 00:50:07.948
these very aggressive glioblastoma tumors.

00:50:07.948 --> 00:50:10.866
The next slide, which has
to do with microcephaly,

00:50:10.866 --> 00:50:12.394
and microcephaly, of
course, is a condition

00:50:12.394 --> 00:50:14.961
where the brain is orders
of magnitude smaller

00:50:14.961 --> 00:50:16.508
than it would normally be.

00:50:16.508 --> 00:50:20.177
The most dramatic cases
of this occurred in Brazil

00:50:20.177 --> 00:50:22.932
last summer when there was an outbreak

00:50:22.932 --> 00:50:25.068
of Zika-induced microcephaly,

00:50:25.068 --> 00:50:28.147
but initially it wasn't
clear that the Zika virus

00:50:28.147 --> 00:50:30.530
was producing the microcephaly.

00:50:30.530 --> 00:50:33.052
We were struck by the fact that literature

00:50:33.052 --> 00:50:35.409
suggested there was one specific factor

00:50:35.409 --> 00:50:38.764
that mediated the entry of
the Zika virus into the skin,

00:50:38.764 --> 00:50:41.678
and that was something
called the AXL receptor.

00:50:41.678 --> 00:50:44.512
And our data set from
the outer radial glia

00:50:44.512 --> 00:50:45.762
that we've been talking
about and the other cells

00:50:45.762 --> 00:50:48.028
in the developing brain
shown here for all of the

00:50:48.028 --> 00:50:51.964
receptors known to mediate
entry of flaviviruses.

00:50:51.964 --> 00:50:53.964
And the Zika virus uses
the ones shown here

00:50:53.964 --> 00:50:56.528
with the black dots to
get into other cell types.

00:50:56.528 --> 00:50:59.299
And I'll emphasize that the AXL receptor,

00:50:59.299 --> 00:51:01.900
which mediates Zika
entry into other cells is

00:51:01.900 --> 00:51:06.066
highly enriched, but only in
certain cells in our data set.

00:51:06.066 --> 00:51:07.795
Shown here it's enriched in astrocytes,

00:51:07.795 --> 00:51:10.763
in radial glial cells, not
intermediate progenitors,

00:51:10.763 --> 00:51:12.580
not in neurons, not in interneurons,

00:51:12.580 --> 00:51:16.026
and also in microglia and endothelium.

00:51:16.026 --> 00:51:18.515
It has a very specific
pattern of expression,

00:51:18.515 --> 00:51:20.004
which we predicted might be the

00:51:20.004 --> 00:51:22.484
tropism of the virus as well.

00:51:22.484 --> 00:51:24.045
That is, the virus would
enter the cells that

00:51:24.045 --> 00:51:25.531
express that receptor.

00:51:25.531 --> 00:51:28.081
So we managed some
collaboration with Joe Darigia

00:51:28.081 --> 00:51:29.499
to get active virus from
a patient who traveled

00:51:29.499 --> 00:51:33.900
to San Francisco from Brazil,
and he was donating blood,

00:51:33.900 --> 00:51:35.828
and the blood actually turned
out to have active virus.

00:51:35.828 --> 00:51:39.004
So we cultured the virus and
exposed our tissue sections.

00:51:39.004 --> 00:51:41.656
Shown here in green is the Zika virus

00:51:41.656 --> 00:51:45.118
reproducing in cells in the
outer subventricular zone,

00:51:45.118 --> 00:51:47.686
which included the
outer radial glial cells

00:51:47.686 --> 00:51:48.684
that I've been talking about.

00:51:48.684 --> 00:51:49.585
It seems to be that they're a

00:51:49.585 --> 00:51:53.254
very favorite target of the Zika virus.

00:51:53.254 --> 00:51:55.670
So shown here, in fact, is
the outer radial glial cell

00:51:55.670 --> 00:52:00.038
packed with the viral particles
just prior to rupture.

00:52:00.038 --> 00:52:01.947
So those outer subventricular
zone cells are specifically

00:52:01.947 --> 00:52:06.584
and especially vulnerable to
infection with the Zika virus.

00:52:06.584 --> 00:52:10.526
When these patients are
born with microcephaly,

00:52:10.526 --> 00:52:13.009
it makes sense, of course, that
the neural progenitor cells

00:52:13.009 --> 00:52:14.424
might be selectively affected,

00:52:14.424 --> 00:52:15.640
and there's much more that goes on

00:52:15.640 --> 00:52:18.140
in this devastating
condition than just infection

00:52:18.140 --> 00:52:19.605
of these outer radial glia, but this seems

00:52:19.605 --> 00:52:22.259
to be a part of the picture.

00:52:22.259 --> 00:52:23.891
And we also took advantage of the fact

00:52:23.891 --> 00:52:28.643
that AXL, we hypothesized, was
mediating entry of the virus

00:52:28.643 --> 00:52:31.351
to block it with a variety
of different chemicals

00:52:31.351 --> 00:52:33.572
and antibodies and
shown here is an example

00:52:33.572 --> 00:52:36.338
of a chemical block of the AXL receptor,

00:52:36.338 --> 00:52:38.650
and these are cultured human cells

00:52:38.650 --> 00:52:39.980
that are exposed to the virus,

00:52:39.980 --> 00:52:42.799
and green dots are the cells
that are actually infected

00:52:42.799 --> 00:52:45.764
with the virus, and if you
block the AXL receptors,

00:52:45.764 --> 00:52:47.902
shown here on the right,
you can significantly reduce

00:52:47.902 --> 00:52:50.550
the cells that get infected.

00:52:50.550 --> 00:52:53.331
Confirming that the AXL
receptors are probably mediating

00:52:53.331 --> 00:52:56.914
entry into at least
these human cell types.

00:52:57.972 --> 00:52:59.483
Now I was very interested,
as I mentioned earlier,

00:52:59.483 --> 00:53:01.694
to find markers or
genes uniquely expressed

00:53:01.694 --> 00:53:04.259
in these outer radial glia
that we could use as a tool

00:53:04.259 --> 00:53:07.779
to try to learn more about the cell types.

00:53:07.779 --> 00:53:09.098
Now we're very gratified
in our first 300 cells

00:53:09.098 --> 00:53:10.514
that we were able to do that.

00:53:10.514 --> 00:53:13.207
Shown on the left are novel markers

00:53:13.207 --> 00:53:14.609
that express themselves only in the

00:53:14.609 --> 00:53:16.969
ventricular radial glia, shown here,

00:53:16.969 --> 00:53:19.018
and on the right are the
more interesting, to me,

00:53:19.018 --> 00:53:22.551
novel gene markers that are expressed in

00:53:22.551 --> 00:53:24.984
outer radial glia only.

00:53:24.984 --> 00:53:28.702
And we justified or rather,
we've validated these markers

00:53:28.702 --> 00:53:30.783
first by showing that they stain cells

00:53:30.783 --> 00:53:33.268
with the morphology and
location of outer radial glia,

00:53:33.268 --> 00:53:36.001
but also dynamically, we
watch cells in our time-lapse

00:53:36.001 --> 00:53:38.613
imaging jump and divide,
and then we fix them

00:53:38.613 --> 00:53:40.273
and stain them with
these markers to confirm

00:53:40.273 --> 00:53:41.200
that the cells that were jumping

00:53:41.200 --> 00:53:44.912
were in fact expressing these
outer radial glial markers,

00:53:44.912 --> 00:53:45.745
and they were.

00:53:45.745 --> 00:53:48.528
So this gives us, now,
a whole new set of tools

00:53:48.528 --> 00:53:51.432
to start looking at these
outer radial glial cells.

00:53:51.432 --> 00:53:53.366
One of the first things we noticed,

00:53:53.366 --> 00:53:56.984
challenges, or I should say
modifies this classic model

00:53:56.984 --> 00:53:59.612
of human cortical, or
primate cortical development

00:53:59.612 --> 00:54:01.185
that Pasko Rakic proposed known as

00:54:01.185 --> 00:54:03.347
the Radial Unit Hypothesis.

00:54:03.347 --> 00:54:06.476
Very influential and
still very very concise

00:54:06.476 --> 00:54:09.313
explanation of how radial units form

00:54:09.313 --> 00:54:13.681
and how they multiply over
time and also evolution.

00:54:13.681 --> 00:54:16.081
And I want to emphasize the
radial glial scaffold here,

00:54:16.081 --> 00:54:18.765
which are all these fibers
go from radial glia down here

00:54:18.765 --> 00:54:21.882
to the cortex along which neurons migrate.

00:54:21.882 --> 00:54:23.682
And the model proposed that this scaffold

00:54:23.682 --> 00:54:26.370
persists throughout cortical development.

00:54:26.370 --> 00:54:28.354
And we were struck,
when we had new markers,

00:54:28.354 --> 00:54:31.081
as I mentioned just a moment
ago, that there seems to be a

00:54:31.081 --> 00:54:34.498
discontinuation of the radial
glial fibers at later stages.

00:54:34.498 --> 00:54:38.170
And that was evident from
these two cell markers.

00:54:38.170 --> 00:54:41.380
In red, I'm showing you HOPX,
which is a gene expressed

00:54:41.380 --> 00:54:44.314
throughout the outer radial
glial cell cytoplasm,

00:54:44.314 --> 00:54:46.095
and you can see red
fibers that you can trace

00:54:46.095 --> 00:54:47.827
all the way up to the pia surface.

00:54:47.827 --> 00:54:49.931
In green is CRYAB, which
is a marker our data

00:54:49.931 --> 00:54:53.865
suggested was only in
ventricular radial glia,

00:54:53.865 --> 00:54:56.181
and the green fibers only went up to the

00:54:56.181 --> 00:54:58.269
outer subventricular zone
and never went further

00:54:58.269 --> 00:55:00.370
at these later stages,

00:55:00.370 --> 00:55:02.248
suggesting that these
fibers and these fibers

00:55:02.248 --> 00:55:05.738
were discontinuous, and we
checked that in a different way

00:55:05.738 --> 00:55:08.730
by using DiI, which is a lipophilic dye

00:55:08.730 --> 00:55:11.822
that can be transported
along radial fibers.

00:55:11.822 --> 00:55:13.554
And if we put those crystals on the top

00:55:13.554 --> 00:55:15.727
or the bottom of this slice, either way,

00:55:15.727 --> 00:55:17.582
we were able to show
these continuous fibers

00:55:17.582 --> 00:55:21.198
at ages up to around gestational week 16.

00:55:21.198 --> 00:55:23.538
But beyond that, the
picture was quite different.

00:55:23.538 --> 00:55:25.928
If we put DiI at the
surface, it backfilled fibers

00:55:25.928 --> 00:55:28.331
only to the outer subventricular zone

00:55:28.331 --> 00:55:30.618
where they end in outer
radial glial cells,

00:55:30.618 --> 00:55:32.785
and if we put the DiI at the ventricle,

00:55:32.785 --> 00:55:35.865
it only went generally as far as the same

00:55:35.865 --> 00:55:38.231
outer subventricular
zone, suggesting a kind of

00:55:38.231 --> 00:55:42.818
a hand-off of cells from
one zone to the other.

00:55:42.818 --> 00:55:45.097
And that led to this
model which is a model

00:55:45.097 --> 00:55:47.634
that suggests that the
second half of neurogenesis,

00:55:47.634 --> 00:55:49.369
the upper cortical layers are produced

00:55:49.369 --> 00:55:52.585
by outer radial glia, not by
these ventricular radial glia,

00:55:52.585 --> 00:55:55.840
which now have transformed
into truncated radial glia.

00:55:55.840 --> 00:55:58.098
So we think there are
three kinds of radial glia

00:55:58.098 --> 00:56:01.137
in human cortical development.

00:56:01.137 --> 00:56:04.231
And we've now expanded
our single cell analysis

00:56:04.231 --> 00:56:06.250
to all these different cell types.

00:56:06.250 --> 00:56:09.280
It's given us an idea
not only of the diversity

00:56:09.280 --> 00:56:11.352
of cell types that are
produced in the human brain

00:56:11.352 --> 00:56:14.570
compared to the mouse,
but we've also identified

00:56:14.570 --> 00:56:19.243
unique markers for each of
these different cell types

00:56:19.243 --> 00:56:20.722
at different stages of development,

00:56:20.722 --> 00:56:24.264
in different brain regions,
and one of them I want

00:56:24.264 --> 00:56:26.833
to mention is DAB1 which
is a reelin affector.

00:56:26.833 --> 00:56:29.882
It's found in radial glia at the ventricle

00:56:29.882 --> 00:56:32.490
and the outer radial glia, but not in the

00:56:32.490 --> 00:56:34.931
truncated radial glia,
which would be here.

00:56:34.931 --> 00:56:36.593
And what's interesting
is that these two cells

00:56:36.593 --> 00:56:38.619
have fibers that go all
the way up to the pia

00:56:38.619 --> 00:56:40.631
where they can receive reelin signaling,

00:56:40.631 --> 00:56:42.137
and the tRG's don't.

00:56:42.137 --> 00:56:44.584
So it very nicely justifies or validates

00:56:44.584 --> 00:56:47.164
the discontinuous glial scaffold model

00:56:47.164 --> 00:56:49.289
that I showed you earlier.

00:56:49.289 --> 00:56:51.060
And then I just wanted
to summarize the points

00:56:51.060 --> 00:56:52.291
that I've made so far,

00:56:52.291 --> 00:56:54.381
that the development or
evolution of these three

00:56:54.381 --> 00:56:57.634
neural stem cell types,
the ventricular, outer,

00:56:57.634 --> 00:57:01.321
and truncated radial glia,
we think help understand

00:57:01.321 --> 00:57:04.417
the expansion and organization
of cerebral cortex.

00:57:04.417 --> 00:57:06.217
That these outer radial
glial cells are enriched

00:57:06.217 --> 00:57:08.632
in self-renewal and proliferation genes,

00:57:08.632 --> 00:57:12.737
and that has led to some
disease associated effects,

00:57:12.737 --> 00:57:14.666
and that the mechanism
for human developmental

00:57:14.666 --> 00:57:17.380
and evolutionary brain
expansion could be co-opted

00:57:17.380 --> 00:57:19.550
in disorders like brain tumors,

00:57:19.550 --> 00:57:22.783
and could be targeted in
disorders such as microcephaly.

00:57:22.783 --> 00:57:24.111
And finally, I want to
thank all the people

00:57:24.111 --> 00:57:27.017
that did all the work,
especially Aparna, Alex, and Tom,

00:57:27.017 --> 00:57:28.233
very gifted post-docs.

00:57:28.233 --> 00:57:31.201
Alex and Tom are setting up
their own labs now at UCSF,

00:57:31.201 --> 00:57:33.441
and our sponsoring organizations.

00:57:33.441 --> 00:57:34.274
Thank you for your attention.

00:57:34.274 --> 00:57:36.169
(applause)

00:57:36.169 --> 00:57:38.669
